First, by Factoring the numerator we can get
\begin{align*} 
x^2 + 10x + 21 &=(x+7)(x+3)\\
&= (x+3)(x+7). 
\end{align*}
This factorization gives us the domain of the expression $\frac{x^2 + 10x + 21}{x^2 + 4x - 21}$ (since the expression is undefined whenever the denominator is zero) as the set
of values of $x$ that are in the domain of
\begin{align*}
\frac{(x+3)(x+7)}{(x+7)(x-3)&= \frac{x+3}{x-3}\quad if\;x\ne 3,7.\\
\end{align*}
The domain of the expression $\frac{(x+3)(x+7)}{(x+7)(x-3)}$, or the set of all values of $x$ that are not equal to 3 and not equal to 7, is the set $\boxed{(-\infty,3)\cup(3,7)\cup(7,\infty)}$.
